# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: upa-upa
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:upa-upa/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Aboriginal people began using dugout canoes from around 1640 in coastal regions of northern Australia.
[src:upa-upa/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] They were brought by Buginese fishers of sea cucumbers, known as trepangers, from Makassar in South Sulawesi.
[src:upa-upa/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] In Arnhem Land, dugout canoes used by the local Yolngu people are called *lipalipa* or *lippa-lippa*.
[src:upa-upa/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Aboriginal canoes were constructed much more easily than previous types of vessels, such as bark canoes.
[src:upa-upa/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] This ease of construction played a significant role in the dugout canoes’ widespread use.
[src:upa-upa/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] While earlier vessels required a great deal of labor and time-consuming sewing to make, dugout canoes were constructed easily and in a shorter period of time.
[src:upa-upa/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] First, one would have to cut down a tree and shape the exterior into an even form.
[src:upa-upa/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] The sides of the canoe were shaped in one of two ways.
[src:upa-upa/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] They were either carved straight up and down or in a "u" shape, curving in towards the center of the boat.
[src:upa-upa/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Next, one would have to dig out the inner wood of the log to make space for the oarsmen to sit and paddle.
[src:upa-upa/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] In some early dugout canoes, Aboriginal people would not make the bottoms of the canoes smooth, but would instead carve "ribbing" into the vessel.
[src:upa-upa/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Ribbing (literally sections of wood that looked like ribs) was used to stabilize bark canoes, and though not necessary to dugout canoes, was a carryover in the transition from one canoe type to the other.
[src:upa-upa/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Both the chopping down of the tree and the digging out of the log were easily done with an iron-axe.
[src:upa-upa/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] The wood used in the construction of dugout canoes was essential to its strength and durability.
[src:upa-upa/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Sycamores are strong and extremely durable, making them suitable for use in the construction of dugout canoes.
[src:upa-upa/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Both sea turtles and dugongs were essential components of the Aboriginal diet.
[src:upa-upa/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] The transformation from bark canoes to dugout canoes greatly increased the ability of the tribal hunters to catch and kill both of these types of sea creatures due primarily to a more formidable structure.
[src:upa-upa/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Dugout canoes included a stronger and better platform for harpooning that greatly increased the stability of an upright hunter by providing essential footing.
[src:upa-upa/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] In order to capture dugongs and sea turtles, the hunters needed to maintain the utmost degree of stealth.
[src:upa-upa/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Perfect balance was required and the new dugout canoes gave the hunters this necessary edge.
[src:upa-upa/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Additionally, the shift towards using dugout canoes maximized the overall possibilities of seafarers.
[src:upa-upa/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Not only did increased sturdiness, speed and stability of Dugout canoes make hunting easier, but these characteristics also allowed for long-distance travel.
[src:upa-upa/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Whereas bark canoes had been only used for inland use or travel extremely close to the shore, Dugout canoes offered a far greater range of travel which allowed for trade outside the area of the village.
[src:upa-upa/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Dugout canoes were capable of traveling distances over 500 km.
[src:upa-upa/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] This new vessel gave the Aboriginal people the ability and opportunity to explore, trade and locate additional resources located outside the central location.
[src:upa-upa/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] The widespread use of dugout canoes had many impacts on Aboriginal life.
[src:upa-upa/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] The most significant were results of the Aboriginal peoples' ability to hunt larger prey.
[src:upa-upa/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] With the strength to transport larger prey over longer distances, dugout enabled the peoples to vastly expand their hunting grounds.
[src:upa-upa/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] This larger prey also enabled support of a larger group of people over a longer period of time.
[src:upa-upa/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] This increase in the ability to support population led to both population growth and expansion.
[src:upa-upa/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Torres Strait Islander people, another Indigenous Australian group of peoples (who are not Aboriginal), used a different type of boat – a double outrigger, unique to their area and probably introduced from Papuan communities and later modified.
[src:upa-upa/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] It was about 14 metres (46 ft) long, with two bamboo masts and sails made of pandanus-mat.
[src:upa-upa/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] They could sail as far as 80 kilometres (50 mi) and carry up to twelve people.
[src:upa-upa/alingano-maisu] The concept for *Alingano Maisu* came about in 2001 when two Hawaiian voyaging groups, the Polynesian Voyaging Society and Na Kalai Waʻa Moku o Hawaiʻi, met with Piailug.
[src:upa-upa/alingano-maisu] The two hulls of the 56-foot (17 m) vessel were fabricated by the Friends of *Hōkūleʻa* and *Hawaiʻiloa* on Oʻahu and shipped to the Island of Hawaiʻi where Na Kalai Waʻa completed construction of the canoe.
[src:upa-upa/alingano-maisu] The Polynesian Voyaging Society provided much of the funding for the voyaging aspect of the project as well as an escort boat to help sail the canoe to Satawal.
[src:upa-upa/alingano-maisu] The canoe is home-ported on the island of Yap under the command of Piailug's son, Sesario Sewralur.
[src:upa-upa/alingano-maisu] Accompanied by *Hōkūleʻa*, the *Maisu* left Kawaihae, Hawaii, on January 18, 2007.
[src:upa-upa/alingano-maisu] After stops in the Marshall Islands, Pohnpei, and Chuuk, the Maisu reached Satawal on March 15, 2007.
[src:upa-upa/alingano-maisu] On March 18, while on Satawal, five native Hawaiian navigators on the voyage were inducted into pwo, a sacred Micronesian brotherhood of master navigators.
[src:upa-upa/alingano-maisu] In June 2008, Palau Community College announced that there will be a one-year program in traditional non-instrumental navigation on the *Alingano Maisu* under Sesario Sewralur.
[src:upa-upa/aloha-festivals] The **Aloha Festivals** are an annual series of free cultural celebrations observed in the state of Hawaii in the United States based on the Makahiki, the beginning of the Native Hawaiian year marked by the sighting of the Pleiades (*Makali'i*).
[src:upa-upa/aloha-festivals] It is the only statewide cultural festival in the nation.
[src:upa-upa/aloha-festivals] Highlights include the presentation of the Royal Court, a ho'olaule'a in Waikiki, and the Floral Parade.
[src:upa-upa/aloha-festivals] Approximately 30,000 people volunteer to plan, organize, and provide labor for the Aloha Festivals each year.
[src:upa-upa/aloha-festivals] Their efforts entertain over 1,000,000 people from throughout the state and visitors from all over the world.
[src:upa-upa/aloha-festivals] In the spirit of preserving the Hawaiian culture and heritage, the Aloha Festivals were established in 1946 as **Aloha Week** by former members of the local Junior Chamber of Commerce.
[src:upa-upa/aloha-festivals] The former manager of the festivals, Goriann Akau, has said, "In 1946, after the war, Hawaiians needed an identity.
[src:upa-upa/aloha-festivals] When we started to celebrate our culture, we began to feel proud.
[src:upa-upa/aloha-festivals] We have a wonderful culture that had been buried for a number of years.
[src:upa-upa/aloha-festivals] The festival was celebrated on six of Hawaii's islands, but in 2008 festival organizers decided to hold most events on Oahu due to a lack of funding.
[src:upa-upa/aloha-festivals] There was also the chance that the Floral Parade would be cancelled altogether, but it was saved by private donors and funds from the City and County of Honolulu.
[src:upa-upa/aloha-festivals] That was caused by the COVID-19 pandemic, a year which had many disruptions.
[src:upa-upa/aloha-festivals] The court is selected from a pool of applicants, all of whom must be of Hawaiian ancestry and of certain ages.
[src:upa-upa/aloha-festivals] The festival itself begins with the presentation of the royal court during the opening ceremony.
[src:upa-upa/aloha-festivals] The ceremony takes place at Helumoa, a section of Waikiki near the Royal Hawaiian Center.
[src:upa-upa/aloha-festivals] The Floral Parade starts at the intersection of Ala Moana Boulevard and Kamakee st. and goes through Waikiki before finishing at Kapiolani Park.
[src:upa-upa/aloha-festivals] The parade features p'au riders, marching bands, hula halaus, and that year's Aloha Festival Royal Court.
[src:upa-upa/aloha-festivals] The Hoʻolauleʻa is a block party held in Waikiki.
[src:upa-upa/aloha-festivals] There is Hawaiian music, hula, and food.
[src:upa-upa/aloha-festivals] Attendance is typically in the thousands.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] The **areca nut**, also called **betel nut**, is the seed of a palm belonging to the areca genus (*Areca catechu*).
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] The palm is originally native to the Philippines, but was carried widely through the tropics by the Austronesian migrations and trade since at least 1500 BCE due to its use in betel nut chewing.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] It is widespread in cultivation and is considered naturalized in much of the tropical Pacific (Melanesia and Micronesia), South Asia, Southeast Asia, and parts of east Africa.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] It is not to be confused with betel (*Piper betle*) leaves that are often used to wrap it.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] The practice of betel nut chewing, often together with other herbs as a stimulant drug, dates back thousands of years, and continues to the present day in many countries.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Areca nut chewing is addictive due to the presence of a stimulant alkaloid, arecoline, and causes adverse health effects, mainly oral and esophageal cancers, as well as cardiovascular disease.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] When chewed with additional tobacco in its preparation (like in gutka), there is an even higher risk, especially for oral and oropharyngeal cancers.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] With tobacco it also raises the risk of fatal coronary artery disease, fatal stroke, and adverse reproductive effects, including stillbirth, premature birth, and low birth weight.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Its consumption by around 600 million people worldwide, mainly of South and Southeast Asian origin, has been described as one of the greatest public health emergencies.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] The terms dates back to the 16th century, when Dutch and Portuguese sailors took the nut from India to Europe.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] The areca nut is not a true nut, but rather the seed of a fruit categorized as a berry.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] It is commercially available in dried, cured, and fresh forms.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] When the husk of the fresh fruit is green, the nut inside is soft enough to be cut with a typical knife.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] In the ripe fruit, the husk becomes yellow or orange, and as it dries, the fruit inside hardens to a wood-like consistency.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] At that stage, the areca nut can only be sliced using a special scissors-like cutter.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Usually, for chewing, a few slices of the nut are wrapped in a betel leaf along with calcium hydroxide (slaked lime) and may include clove, cardamom, catechu resin (*kattha*), or other spices for extra flavouring.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Betel leaf has a fresh, peppery taste, but it can also be bitter to varying degrees, depending on the variety.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Areca nuts are chewed for their effects as a mild stimulant, causing a warming sensation in the body and slightly heightened alertness, although the effects vary from person to person.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] In parts of India, Sri Lanka, southern China, and Southeast Asia, areca nuts are not only chewed along with betel leaf, but are also used in the preparation of Ayurvedic and traditional Chinese medicines.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Powdered areca nut is used as a constituent in some dentifrices.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Other traditional uses include the removal of tapeworms and other intestinal parasites by swallowing a few teaspoons of powdered areca nut, drunk as a decoction, or by taking tablets containing the extracted alkaloids.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] According to traditional Ayurvedic medicine, chewing areca nut and betel leaf is a good remedy against bad breath.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Diplomat Edmund Roberts noted that Chinese people would mix areca nut with *Uncaria gambir* during his visit to China in the 1830s.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] After chewing a betel nut, the red residue is generally spat out.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Accordingly, places have banned chewing this nut to avoid eyesores.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] The major alkaloid in betel nut is arecoline, a non-selective partial agonist of muscarinic and nicotinic acetylcholine receptors.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] There are other compounds, such as arecaidine, guvacine, isoguvacine, and guvacoline.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Tannins present in betel nut are mainly proanthocyanidins along with catechins and arecatannin.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Two new alkaloids were recently discovered and named acatechu A and acatechu B.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Several non-alkaloid compounds including benzenoids, terpenes, carboxylic acids, aldehydes, alcohols, and esters were also identified.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Chewing areca nut increases the risk of multiple forms of cancer and cardiovascular disease, with or without added tobacco.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Betel nut chewing causes an increased risk of head and neck cancers and esophageal cancer.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Betel quid affects almost all parts of the human body, including the brain, heart, lungs, gastrointestinal tract and reproductive organs.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] It can cause myocardial infarction, cardiac arrhythmias, liver damage, asthma, type II diabetes, hyperlipidemia, metabolic syndrome, hypothyroidism, prostate hyperplasia and infertility.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Habitual chewing of areca nuts increases the risk of cirrhosis and hepatocellular carcinoma.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Chewing areca nuts is a cause of oral submucous fibrosis, a condition which may progress to mouth cancer.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] It has also been linked to throat cancer.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] When chewed with additional tobacco in its preparation (like in gutka), there is an even higher risk for cancer, especially for oral and oropharyngeal cancers.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] The harm caused by consumption of areca nuts worldwide was classified in 2017 as a "neglected global public health emergency".
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Indian government and agriculture ministry is probing the IARC report as a misconception.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Significant opposition and contradictions in the IARC report has been reported in India.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] One such contradiction being, Arecoline, one of arecanut's principal constituents, is classified under Group II B (possibly carcinogenic to humans).
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Women who chew areca nut formulations, such as *paan*, during pregnancy significantly increase adverse outcomes for the baby.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Betel quid chewing can cause stillbirth, premature birth, and low birth weight.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Using tobacco or areca nuts during pregnancy significantly increases adverse outcomes for the baby.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] The habit is associated with higher incidences of preterm birth and low birth weight and height.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Biologically, these effects may be a consequence of the arecoline that is found in areca nuts.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] The habit also exposes the fetus to various other toxic components linked to cancer.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] In 2023, world production of areca nuts was 2.3 million tonnes, with India providing 60% of the total and Bangladesh and Myanmar as major secondary producers (table).
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] State of Karnataka in India alone produced 79.97% of country's overall production (2019-20).
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] In India (the largest consumer of areca nut) and the rest of the Indian subcontinent, the preparation of nut with or without betel leaf is commonly referred to as paan.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] It is available practically everywhere and is sold in ready-to-chew pouches called *pan masala* or *supari*, which is the dried form of the areca nut, as a mixture of many flavours whose primary base is dried areca nut crushed into small pieces.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Poor people, who may eat only every other day, use it to stave off hunger pangs.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] *Pan masala* with a small quantity of tobacco is called *gutka*.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] The easily discarded, small plastic *supari* or *gutka* pouches are a ubiquitous pollutant of the South Asian environment.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Some of the liquid in the mouth is usually disposed of by spitting, producing bright red spots wherever the expectorate lands.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] In the Maldives, areca nut chewing is very popular, but spitting is frowned upon and regarded as an unrefined, repulsive way of chewing.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Usually, people prefer to chew thin slices of the dry nut, which is sometimes roasted.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] *Killi*, a mixture of areca nut, betel, cloves, cardamom and sugar is sold in small home-made paper pouches.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Old people who have lost their teeth keep "chewing" by pounding the mixture of areca nut and betel with a small mortar and pestle.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] In Thailand, the consumption of areca nut has declined gradually in the last decades.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] The younger generation rarely chews the substance, especially in the cities.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Most of the present-day consumption is confined to older generations, mostly people above 50.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Even so, small trays of betel leaves and sliced tender areca nut are sold in markets and used as offerings in Buddhist shrines.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] In the northern Philippines, particularly the Cordillera Administrative Region, betel nut chewing remains prominent to the point that restrictions and fines have been established in urban areas such as Baguio City in the Benguet province.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] These restrictions were made under the idea that *momma* or *moma* (betel nut) chewing and spitting are improper during public transportation drivers' work hours and are considered stains to the city roads and sidewalks.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Despite these restrictions, betel nut thrives across the Cordilleran market.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] An example of its commerciality can be observed in Ifugao, one of the provinces of the Philippine Cordilleras, where betel nuts are high-demand products sourced from the province's different cities and municipalities.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] In Bahasa Indonesia, the betel nut is known as *makan pinang*, while in the Papua Province of Indonesia, it is known simply as *pinang*.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] The Pinang scissor was developed specifically for cutting it.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] In Papua New Guinea (PNG), betel nuts are referred to in Tok Pisin as *buai*, and grow abundantly on the northern coast, in Wewak and Madang.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] A controversial ban on selling and chewing betel nut in public places in Port Moresby, introduced in 2014 by the governor, was lifted in 2017.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Because the popular nut continued to be smuggled in, prices rose dramatically.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Police enforced the ban rigorously, and in 2015 two betel nut sellers died in Hanuabada after police reservists fired on a crowd.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] The governor of Port Moresby introduced another ban on the nut, restricted to an area in the business district of the city in July 2023.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] However many people make a living out of selling betel nut, so are resistant to bans in their areas.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] On Manus Island, young men are exposed to piracy when they use small boats to travel to the northern coast to purchase betel nuts to trade, and several have disappeared.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] In Australia, the importation, use, and sale of areca nut is banned, but it has been sold illegally in several South Asian supermarkets.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] In Hainan and Hunan Province, China, where Xiangtan is a center of use and processing, a wide range of old and young people consume areca nut daily.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Most, though, consume the dried variety of the nut by itself, without the betel leaves.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Some people also consume the areca nut in its raw, fresh form with or without the betel leaves.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Betel nuts are sold mostly by old women merchants, but the dried version can be found in shops that sell tea, alcohol, and cigarettes.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] In Taiwan, bags of 20 to 40 areca nuts are purchased fresh daily by a large number of consumers.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] The latter is usually elevated one meter above the street, and measures less than 3 by 2 m.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Large picture windows comprise two or more of the walls, allowing those who pass by a complete view of the interior.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Within such a shop, a sexily dressed young woman, a "betel nut beauty", can be seen preparing betel and areca nuts.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Shops are often identified by colorful (commonly green) LED lamps or neon lights that frame the windows or that are arranged radially above a store.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Customers stop on the side of the road and wait for the girls to bring their betel and areca nut to their vehicles.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] The habit of chewing betel nut is often associated with blue-collar labor industries such as long-haul transportation, construction, or fishing.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Workers in these labor-intensive industries use betel nut for its stimulating effect, but it also becomes a tool for socializing with coworkers.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] For example, studies have shown chewing betel nut is prevalent among taxi, bus and truck drivers, who rely on the stimulating effect of betel nut to cope with long work hours.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] For these reasons, oral cancer has been identified as a leading cause of death in professions with high betel nut-chewing rates.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] In the United States, areca nut is not a controlled or specially taxed substance and may be found in some Asian grocery stores.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] However, importation of areca nut in a form other than whole or carved kernels of nuts can be stopped at the discretion of US Customs officers on the grounds of food, agricultural, or medicinal drug violations.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] In the United Kingdom the betel nut is legal.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Possession of areca nut or betel leaf is banned in the UAE and is a punishable offence.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Chewing the mixture of areca nut and betel leaf constitutes an important and popular cultural activity in many South Asian, Southeast Asian, East Asian and Oceanic countries.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Why or when the areca nut and the betel leaf were first combined into one psychoactive drug is not known.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Archaeological evidence from Thailand, Indonesia, and the Philippines suggests they have been used in tandem for at least 4,000 years.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] The oldest unequivocal evidence of betel chewing is from the Philippines, specifically that of several individuals found in a burial pit in the Duyong Cave site of Palawan island dated to around 2680±250 BCE.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] The dentition of the skeletons is stained, typical of betel chewers.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] The grave also includes *Anadara* shells used as containers of lime, one of which still contained lime.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Burial sites in Bohol dated to the first millennium CE also show the distinctive reddish stains characteristic of betel chewing.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] From the Philippines, it spread back to Taiwan, as well as onwards to the rest of Austronesia and in neighboring cultures through trade and migration.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] In Vietnam, the areca nut and the betel leaf are such important symbols of love and marriage that in Vietnamese the phrase "matters of betel and areca" (*chuyện trầu cau*) is synonymous with marriage.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] The tradition of chewing areca nuts starts the talk between the groom's parents and the bride's parents about the young couple's marriage.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Therefore, the leaves and juices are used ceremonially in Vietnamese weddings.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] The folk tale explaining the origin of this Vietnamese tradition is a good illustration of the belief that the combination of areca nut and the betel leaf is ideal to the point they are practically inseparable, like an idealized married couple.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Formerly, in both India and Sri Lanka, it was a custom of the royalty to chew areca nut with betel leaf.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Kings had special attendants whose duty it was to carry a box with all the necessary ingredients for a good chewing session.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] There was also a custom for lovers to chew areca nut and betel leaf together, because of its breath-freshening and relaxant properties.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] A sexual symbolism thus became attached to the chewing of the nut and the leaf.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] The areca nut represented the male principle, and the betel leaf the female principle.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Considered an auspicious ingredient in Hinduism and some schools of Buddhism, the areca nut is still used along with betel leaf in religious ceremonies, and also while honoring individuals in much of southern Asia.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] In Assam, as well as most of its neighbouring Northeastern India states, areca nuts are preferably consumed in fermented form, which is supposed to make the fruit harder and sweeter.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] The raw nut may also be eaten during certain seasons when the fermented variety becomes unavailable, although it has more ritual importance.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Standard-sized pieces of the nut and leaf are usually consumed in combination with lime and a bit of tobacco.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] In Assam, betel nut and leaf has indispensable cultural value; offering betel leaf and nut, (together known as *gua*) constitutes a part of social greeting and socialising.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] It is a tradition to offer *pan-tamul* (betel leaves and raw areca nut) to guests immediately upon arrival, and after tea or meals, served in a brass plate with stands called *bota*.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] In traditional Assamese societies carrying a pouch of *tamul-pan* upon one's person during journeys or during farming activities, and sharing of the same, was an essential requirement.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Among the Assamese, the areca nut also has a variety of uses during religious and marriage ceremonies, where it has the role of a fertility symbol.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] No religious ritual is complete without the offering of *tamul-pan* to the gods and spirits as well as to the assembled guests.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] A tradition from Upper Assam is to invite guests to wedding receptions by offering a few areca nuts with betel leaves.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] During Bihu, the *husori* players are offered areca nuts and betel leaves by each household while their blessings are solicited.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Spanish mariner Álvaro de Mendaña reported observing Solomon Islanders chewing the nut and the leaf with caustic lime, and the manner in which the habit stained their mouths red.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] He noted the friendly and genial chief Malope, on Santa Isabel Island, would offer him the combination as a token of friendship every time they met.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] In Bhutan, the areca nut is called *doma*.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] The soft and moist raw areca nut is very potent.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] When chewed it can cause palpitation and vasoconstriction.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] This form is eaten in the lower regions of Bhutan and in North Bengal, where the nut is cut into half and put into a local *paan* leaf with a generous amount of lime.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] In the rest of Bhutan the raw nut, with the husk on, is fermented such that the husk rots and is easy to extract.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] The fermented doma has a putrid odour, which can be smelled at a distance.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Traditionally, the fragrant nut is cut in half and placed on top of a cone made of local betel leaf, which has a dash of lime put inside.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] "Myth has it that the inhabitants of Bhutan traditionally known as Monyul, the land of Monpas where Buddhism did not reach lived on raw flesh, drank blood, and chewed bones.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] After the arrival of Guru Rinpoche in the eighth century, he stopped the people from eating flesh and drinking blood and created a substitute which is betel leaf, lime and areca nut.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Today, chewing doma has become a custom.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Doma is served after meals, during rituals and ceremonies.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] The addition of tobacco leaf to the chewing mixture is a relatively recent innovation, as tobacco was not introduced from the Americas until the colonial era.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Reasons for starting to consume areca nuts appears to involve complex psychosocial factors.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] The husk, which is between 50 and 75 percent of the weight and volume of an areca fruit, serves as a source of fiber for the construction industry.
[src:upa-upa/areca-nut] Typically, these fibers are considered to be waste, but can be used to strengthen construction materials.
[src:upa-upa/asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium] Since its creation, AAPIPRC has sponsored annual conferences focused on connecting national, state and local agencies to AAPI policy and research.
[src:upa-upa/asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium] Hosted by the National Education Association in Washington D.C., the 2012 conference focused on "Expanding the Asian American and Pacific Islander Voice in National Policy." The 2013 conference focused on the use of survey and other research methodology to inform AAPI policy.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] Many of the constellations were given names based on their shapes, just as traditional western astronomy does, such as the Pleiades, Orion and the Milky Way, with others, such as Emu in the Sky, describes the dark patches rather than the points lit by the stars.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] Contemporary Indigenous Australian art often references astronomical subjects and their related lore, such as the Seven Sisters.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] One of the earliest written records of Aboriginal astronomy was made by William Edward Stanbridge, an Englishman who emigrated to Australia in 1841 and befriended the local Boorong people.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] A constellation used almost everywhere in Australian Aboriginal culture is the "Emu in the Sky", which consists of dark nebulae (opaque clouds of dust and gas in outer space) that are visible against the (centre and other sectors of the) Milky Way background.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The Emu's head is the very dark Coalsack Nebula, next to the Southern Cross; the body and legs are that extension of the Great Rift trailing out to Scorpius.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] In Ku-ring-gai Chase National Park, north of Sydney, are extensive rock engravings of the Guringai people who lived there, including representations of the creator-hero Daramulan and his emu-wife.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] An engraving near the Elvina Track shows an emu in the same pose and orientation as the Emu in the Sky constellation.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] To the Wardaman, however, the Coalsack is the head of a lawman.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] Bruce Pascoe's 2014 book *Dark Emu* takes its title from one of the Aboriginal names for the constellation, known as Gugurmin to the Wiradjuri people.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] In May 2020, the Royal Australian Mint launched a limited edition commemorative one-dollar coin, as the first in its "Star Dreaming" series celebrating Indigenous Australians' astrology.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The Yolŋu people of northern Australia say that the constellation of Orion, which they call Julpan (or Djulpan), is a canoe.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] They tell the story of three brothers who went fishing, and one of them ate a sawfish that was forbidden under their law.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] Seeing this, the Sun-woman, Walu, made a waterspout that carried him and his two brothers and their canoe up into the sky.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The three stars that line in the constellation's centre, which form Orion's Belt in Western mythology, are the three brothers; the Orion Nebula above them is the forbidden fish; and the bright stars Betelgeuse and Rigel are the bow and stern of the canoe.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] This is an example of astronomical legends underpinning the ethical and social codes that people use on Earth.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The Pleiades constellation figures in the Dreamings and songlines of several Aboriginal Australian peoples, usually referred to as the seven sisters.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The story also includes Warlpiri lands, the Tanami Desert of the Northern Territory.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The Yamatji people of the Wajarri language group, of the Murchison region in Western Australia, call the sisters Nyarluwarri.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] When the constellation is close to the horizon as the sun is setting, the people know that it is the right time to harvest emu eggs, and they also use the brightness of the stars to predict seasonal rainfall.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] In the Kimberley region of Western Australia, the eagle hawk chases the seven sisters up into the sky, where they become the star cluster and he becomes the Southern Cross.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] In the Western Desert cultural bloc in central Australia, they are said to be seven sisters fleeing from the unwelcome attentions of a man represented by some of the stars in Orion, the hunter.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] In these stories, the man is called Nyiru or Nirunja, and the Seven Sisters is songline known as *Kungkarangkalpa*.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The Museum of Contemporary Art Australia in Sydney holds a 2013 work by the Tjanpi Desert Weavers called *Minyma Punu Kungkarangkalpa* (Seven Sisters Tree Women).
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] In March 2013, senior desert dancers from the APY Lands (South Australia) in collaboration with the Australian National University's ARC Linkage and mounted by artistic director Wesley Enoch, performed *Kungkarangkalpa: The Seven Sisters Songline* on the shores of Lake Burley Griffin in Canberra.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] In the Warlpiri version of the story, the Napaljarri sisters are often represented carrying a man called Wardilyka, who is in love with the women.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] But the morning star, Jukurra-jukurra, a man from a different skin group and who is also in love with the sisters, chases them across the sky.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] Each night they launch themselves into the sky, and each night he follows them.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] This story is known as the *Napaljarri-warnu Jukurrpa*.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The people of around Lake Eyre in South Australia tell how the ancestor male is prevented from capturing one of the seven sisters by a great flood.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The Wirangu people of the west coast of South Australia have a creation story embodied in a songline of great significance based on the Pleiades.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] In the story, the hunter (the Orion constellation) is named Tgilby.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] Tgilby, after falling in love with the seven sisters, known as Yugarilya, chases them out of the sky, onto and across the earth.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] He chases them as the Yugarilya chase a snake, Dyunu.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The Boonwurrung people of the Kulin nation of Victoria tell the Karatgurk story, which tells of how a crow robbed the seven sisters of their secret of how to make fire, thus bringing the skill to the people on earth.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] In another story, told by peoples of New South Wales, the seven sisters are beautiful women known as the Maya-Mayi, two of whom are kidnapped by a warrior, Warrumma, or Warunna.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] They eventually escape by climbing a pine tree that continually grows up into the sky where they join their other sisters.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] In 2017, a major exhibition entitled *Songlines: Tracking the Seven Sisters* was mounted at the National Museum of Australia, afterwards travelling to Berlin (2022) and Paris (2023).
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] In September 2020, the Royal Australian Mint issued its second commemorative one-dollar coin in its "Star Dreaming" series celebrating Indigenous Australians' astrology (see Emu in the sky above).
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The Kaurna people of the Adelaide Plains of South Australia called the (centre and other sectors of) the Milky Way *wodliparri* in the Kaurna language, meaning "house river".
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] They believed that Karrawirra Parri (the River Torrens) was a reflection of wodliparri.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The Yolŋu people believe that when they die, they are taken by a mystical canoe, *Larrpan*, to the spirit-island Baralku in the sky, where their camp-fires can be seen burning along the edge of the great river of the Milky Way.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The canoe is sent back to Earth as a shooting star, letting their family on Earth know that they have arrived safely in the spirit-land.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] Aboriginals also thought that god was the canoe.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The Boorong people see in the Southern Cross a possum in a tree.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] Many traditions have stories of a female Sun and a male Moon.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The Yolŋu say that Walu, the Sun-woman, lights a small fire each morning, which we see as the dawn.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] She paints herself with red ochre, some of which spills onto the clouds, creating the sunrise.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] She then lights a torch and carries it across the sky from east to west, creating daylight.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] At the end of her journey, as she descends from the sky, some of her ochre paints again rubs off onto the clouds, creating the sunset.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] She then puts out her torch, and throughout the night travels underground back to her starting camp in the east.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] Other Aboriginal peoples of the Northern Territory call her Wuriupranili.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] Other stories about the Sun involve Wala, Yhi, and Gnowee.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The Yolŋu tell that Ngalindi, the Moon-man, was once young and slim (the waxing Moon), but grew fat and lazy (the full Moon).
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] His wives chopped bits off him with their axes (the waning Moon); to escape them he climbed a tall tree towards the Sun, but died from the wounds (the new Moon).
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] After remaining dead for three days, he rose again to repeat the cycle, and continues doing so till this day.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The Kuwema people in the Northern Territory say that he grows fat at each full Moon by devouring the spirits of those who disobey the tribal laws.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] Another story by the Aboriginals of Cape York involves the making of a giant boomerang that is thrown into the sky and becomes the Moon.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] A story from Southern Victoria concerns a beautiful woman who is forced to live by herself in the sky after a number of scandalous affairs.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The Yolŋu also associated the Moon with the tides.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The Warlpiri people explain a solar eclipse as being the Sun-woman being hidden by the Moon-man as he makes love to her.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] This explanation is shared by other groups, such as the Wirangu.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] In the Ku-ring-gai Chase National Park there are a number of engravings showing a crescent shape, with sharp horns pointing down, and below it a drawing of a man in front of a woman.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] While the crescent shape has been assumed by most researchers to represent a boomerang, some argue that it is more easily interpreted as a solar eclipse, with the mythical man-and-woman explanation depicted below it.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The rising of Venus marks an important ceremony of the Yolŋu, who call it Barnumbirr ("Morning Star and Evening Star").
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] They gather after sunset to await the rising of the planet.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The Dja Dja Wurrung call Jupiter "Bunjil's campfire".
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The planet features in the Dja Dja Wurrung Aboriginal Clans Corporation logo, as a symbol of the Creator Spirit.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] This is the only definitive indigenous record of Eta Carinae's outburst identified in the literature to date.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] Aboriginal calendars tend to differ from European calendars: many groups in northern Australia use a calendar with six seasons, and some groups mark the seasons by the stars which are visible during them.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] For the Pitjantjatjara, for example, the rising of the Pleiades at dawn (in May) marks the start of winter.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] It is not known to what extent Aboriginal people were interested in the precise motion of the sun, moon, planets or stars.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] However, it likely that some of the stone arrangements in Victoria such as Wurdi Youang near Little River, Victoria, may have been used to predict and confirm the equinoxes and/or solstices.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The arrangement is aligned with the setting sun at the solstices and equinox, but its age is unknown.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] There are rock engravings by the Nganguraku people at Ngaut Ngaut which, according to oral tradition, represent lunar cycles.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] Most of their culture (including their language) has been lost because of the banning of such things by Christian missionaries before 1913.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] Stories enrich a custom-linked calendar whereby the heliacal rising or setting of stars or constellations indicates to Aboriginal Australians when it is time to move to a new place and/or look for a new food source.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] For example, the Boorong people in Victoria know that when *the Malleefowl* (Lyra) disappears in October, to "sit with the Sun", it is time to start gathering her eggs on Earth.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] Other groups know that when Orion first appears in the sky, the dingo puppies are about to be born.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] When Scorpius appears, the Yolŋu know that the Macassan fisherman would soon arrive to fish for trepang.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] A great deal of contemporary Aboriginal art has an astronomical theme, reflecting the astronomical elements of the artists' cultures.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] Prominent examples are Gulumbu Yunupingu, Bill Yidumduma Harney, and Nami Maymuru, all of whom have won awards or been finalists in the Telstra Indigenous Art Awards.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] In 2009 an exhibition of Indigenous Astronomical Art from WA, named "Ilgarijiri", was launched at AIATSIS in Canberra in conjunction with a Symposium on Aboriginal Astronomy.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] Other contemporary painters include the daughters of the late Clifford Possum Tjapaltjarri, who have the seven sisters as one of their Dreamings.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] Gabriella Possum and Michelle Possum paint the Seven Sisters Dreaming in their paintings.
[src:upa-upa/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] They inherited this Dreaming through their maternal line.
[src:upa-upa/ote-a] The **ʻōteʻa** (usually written as *otea*) is a traditional dance and accompanying music from Tahiti characterized by a rapid hip-shaking motion to percussion accompaniment.
[src:upa-upa/ote-a] The dancers, standing in several rows, may be further choreographed to execute different figures (including tamau, varu, otamu, ami, and fa'arapu) while maintaining the hip-shaking.
[src:upa-upa/ote-a] The hip motion itself may in some choreographies be synchronized amongst multiple dancers and may be further coordinated with the accompanying percussion arrangement.
[src:upa-upa/ote-a] The dance is with music only (drums) at a fast rhythm, and no singing.
[src:upa-upa/ote-a] The drum can be one of the different types of the *tōʻere*, a lying log of wood with a longitudinal slit, which is struck by one or two sticks.
[src:upa-upa/ote-a] Additional drum types accompanying the dance may include the ng drum covered with a shark skin and struck by the hands or with sticks) played at a slower rhythm, or the smaller *faʻatētē* drum.
[src:upa-upa/ote-a] The ʻōteʻa is one of the few dances which already existed in pre-European times as a male dance.
[src:upa-upa/ote-a] (The *hura* (Tahitian vernacular for hula), a dance for women, on the other hand has disappeared, and likewise is gone the couple's dance ʻupaʻupa but which may have reemerged as the tāmūrē).
[src:upa-upa/ote-a] Nowadays, however the ʻōteʻa can be danced by men (ʻōteʻa tāne), by women (ʻōteʻa vahine), or by both genders (ʻōteʻa ʻāmui = united ʻō.).
[src:upa-upa/ote-a] Dancers of the ʻōteʻa make gestures reenacting daily occupations of life.
[src:upa-upa/ote-a] For the men the gestural themes can be chosen from warfare or sailing, and then they may use spears or paddles.
[src:upa-upa/ote-a] For women the gestural themes are typically closer to home or from nature: hand gestures suggesting combing their hair, or the flight of a butterfly.
[src:upa-upa/ote-a] More elaborate themes have been adopted; for example one where the dancers end up in a map of Tahiti, highlighting important places.
[src:upa-upa/ote-a] In a proper ʻōteʻa the story of the theme should pervade the whole dance.
[src:upa-upa/ote-a] The costumes are extremely elaborate, typically incorporating long plant fiber ("grass") skirts, belting with tassels that accentuate the hip-motion, may further include decorated headpieces, and may be color-coordinated across the dancers of the company.
[src:upa-upa/ote-a] The same *more* dress and the same shaking of the knees for the boys and of the hips for the girls as in all Tahitian dances (see tāmūrē) is used here too.
[src:upa-upa/ote-a] Interpretations of the **ʻōteʻa** are frequently included as part of larger Polynesian dance recitals presented at luaus and visitor-oriented live shows in the Hawaiian Islands and other Pacific-rim resorts outside Tahiti.
[src:upa-upa/ote-a] Modern drum accompaniments may include drums of European or non-Pacific construction, improvised percussion instruments of modern materials (e.g. high-density polyethylene or metallic commercial food packaging), and the use of prerecorded drum reinforcement soundtracks.
[src:upa-upa/upa-upa] The **ʼupaʼupa** (often written as **upa upa**) is a traditional dance from Tahiti.
[src:upa-upa/upa-upa] It was mentioned by European explorers, who described it as very indecent.
[src:upa-upa/upa-upa] It is not quite clear how similar the gestures at that time were with the now immensely popular tāmūrē.
[src:upa-upa/upa-upa] In both dances the performers form groups of pairs of a boy and a girl, dancing more or less in sexually oriented movements.
[src:upa-upa/upa-upa] The musical setting usually includes voice, flute, and drums.
[src:upa-upa/upa-upa] After having arrived on Tahiti in 1797, the LMS missionaries quickly intimidated the local rulers of the island and fixed themselves in a position of power.
[src:upa-upa/upa-upa] Although this enabled them to abolish such habits as infanticide, cannibalism and tribal wars, it also enabled them to introduce the idea of sin, which was unknown on Tahiti until then.
[src:upa-upa/upa-upa] The joy of dancing, so dear to the Polynesian heart, was one of the first to be axed.
[src:upa-upa/upa-upa] The famous Pōmare code of 1819 declared the ʼupaʼupa (and tattooing in the same line) to be bad and immoral habitudes, severely to be opposed.
[src:upa-upa/upa-upa] In the code of 1842 many restrictions were relaxed, but the ʼupaʼupa (the general term for dancing then) remained on the black list.
[src:upa-upa/upa-upa] In the same year the French proclaimed the protectorate.
[src:upa-upa/upa-upa] Being Catholic with some broader views on life than the Protestants, and considering that "if you cannot beat them, join them", they proclaimed in the official bulletin of 1849 that the ʼupaʼupa was still forbidden, except on public feastdays, but then still without the indecent gestures.
[src:upa-upa/upa-upa] The act of 1853, repeated in 1876 was more restrictive.
[src:upa-upa/upa-upa] In the hope that the Tahitians would spend their time on more pious occupations than dancing and drinking, a system of licenses was introduced.
[src:upa-upa/upa-upa] A license could only be obtained by a chef and only on Saturday evenings.
[src:upa-upa/upa-upa] Despite all these restrictions, dancing went on, less secret or more secret depending on the law at that moment.
[src:upa-upa/upa-upa] Nevertheless, many years of suppression had left a mark on it, and although the idea and the steps were still there, the ʼupaʼupa of the old did not really exist anymore.
[src:upa-upa/upa-upa] In the beginning of the 20th century Tahitian dances were only performed on such festivities as 14 July and saw an evolution into what they have become nowadays.
[src:upa-upa/upa-upa] Around 1900 the traditional costumes came back, and although they still looked more like mother Hubbard dresses or ponchos, at least they were made of traditional materials.
[src:upa-upa/upa-upa] Around 1920 strips of raffia were added, which soon would develop into the characteristic *more* or grass skirt (in reality made from hibiscus fibers) of Tahiti.
[src:upa-upa/upa-upa] The bare torso (for men only) became acceptable.
[src:upa-upa/upa-upa] Prizes started to be awarded to the best dancers on a festival.
[src:upa-upa/upa-upa] But it was not until 1956 that Madeleine Mouʼa organised a dance group, called the *heiva*, of which Teriʼi and Takau, daughters of the last queen of Tahiti became patrons.
[src:upa-upa/upa-upa] Finally then traditional dancing had the blessing from the establishment.
[src:upa-upa/upa-upa] The opening of Faaʼa International Airport in 1961 and the real start of the tourist industry on Tahiti made all the dances which had come forth from the ʼupaʼupa a part of daily life once more.
